1 Lesson 4: mutating joins 2

1.1 Learning objectives

  1. Mutating joins functions in practice
  2. filtering join verbs

In the current lesson we will learn about the last 2 mutating join functions:

  • inner_join()

  • full_join()

furthermore, we will also consider 2 more advanced functions which are defined as filtering join verbs

  • semi_join()

  • anti_join()

library(here)
library(dplyr)
library(readr)

1.1.1 inner_join

The inner_join() simply returns all the rows that have a match in the second dataframe

Source: PsyTeachR

To test this function we call back the dataframes we used in the previous lesson

yaounde <- 
  read_csv(file = here("chapter_xxx_tidy_data/data/yaounde_covid_seroprev_dataset.csv"), show_col_types = FALSE)

yaounde_1 <- 
  yaounde %>%
  select("id_quest", "n_hhld_rooms", "n_hhld_adults", "n_hhld_children") %>%
  slice(2:25)

yaounde_2 <- 
  yaounde %>%
  select("id_quest", "loc_hhld_area", "loc_hhld_lat", "loc_hhld_long") %>%
  slice(2:20)
yaounde_inner_j <-
  inner_join(yaounde_1, yaounde_2, by = "id_quest")

yaounde_inner_j

inner_join() will return 19 columns because those are the column that corresponds between the 2 dataframes based on the âid_questâ criteria

1.1.2 full_join

full_join() retain all the rows from the 2 dataframes. When a match is not possible between the dataframes, the rows of the dataframe where the match is missing are filled with NA (similar to what we saw in lesson 3 with left_join)

Source: PsyTeachR 

yaounde_full_j <-
  full_join(yaounde_1, yaounde_2, by = "id_quest")

yaounde_full_j
## # A tibble: 24 x 7
##    id_quest             n_hhld_rooms n_hhld_adults n_hhld_children loc_hhld_area
##    <chr>                       <dbl>         <dbl>           <dbl> <chr>        
##  1 CARRIERE/NUM/002/00~            2             3               1 carriere     
##  2 CARRIERE/NUM/002/00~            2             3               1 carriere

Now we can explore the filtering_joins() functions

1.1.3 semi_join

semi_join() purpose is not to join data but is rather filtering the dataframe on the left based on the matching criteria with the right dataframe

Source: PsyTeachR 

yaounde_semi_j <-
  semi_join(yaounde_1, yaounde_2, by = "id_quest")

yaounde_semi_j
## # A tibble: 19 x 4
##    id_quest                 n_hhld_rooms n_hhld_adults n_hhld_children
##    <chr>                           <dbl>         <dbl>           <dbl>
##  1 CARRIERE/NUM/002/0001               2             3               1
##  2 CARRIERE/NUM/002/0002               2             3               1
##  3 CARRIERE/NUM/038/0002               5             2               4

##  8 BRIQUETERIE/NUM/019/0004            7             7               1
##  9 CARRIERE/NUM/014/0004               4             5               0
## 10 BRIQUETERIE/NUM/014/0006            4             6               0

## 18 EKOUDOU/NUM/032/0001                2             2               2
## 19 EKOUDOU/NUM/002/0001                6             9               6

As you see, it returns a dataframe of dimension 19 X 4 where 19 are the matching rows and 4 are the columns from yaounde_1. Interestingly, if you try to duplicate the values in the right dataframe (yaounde_2) semi_join() will produce the exact same result because duplicates are not considered. Indeed, the purpose of the second dataframe is just to provide a key to filter the left dataframe

yaounde_2 <- 
  yaounde_2 %>% 
  slice(rep(1:n(), each = 2))  
yaounde_semi_j <-
  semi_join(yaounde_1, yaounde_2, by = "id_quest")

yaounde_semi_j

1.1.4 anti_join

Source: PsyTeachR

the last function we cover in this lesson is anti_join() and its function is the opposite of semi_join() i.e.Â return all the values that are not matching with the right dataframe

#restore yaounde_2 without duplicates 
yaounde_2 <- 
  yaounde %>%
  select("id_quest", "loc_hhld_area", "loc_hhld_lat", "loc_hhld_long") %>%
  slice(2:20)
yaounde_anti_j <-
  anti_join(yaounde_1, yaounde_2, by = "id_quest")

yaounde_anti_j
